description:
Ok, yeah, I know, here is two observations of the same species on the same day and place. But I kinda want to keep these separate. I found other B. chrysenteron which match what I know, and I have other photos here. But I also found these growing close by, and these were a little more abundant. But these are too thin, the caps too cracked and so deeply, and with no evindence of a pink layer to show between the cracks. Also the flesh doesn’t stain at all, anywhere, only the pores showed blue staining.

But looking in the Boletes of CA by Thiers, B. chrysenteron is the only one that comes up really, or B. truncatus, but that overlaps chrysenteron in macroscopic features. So, I don’t know. I feal like these are different than B. chrysenteron, but there really isn’t anything else they probably are…
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

I need to look at these some more, looking things over I think C. glaucopus is closer to right.

description:
Ok, I don’t like this id, but it is as close as I get. I found these by themselves, and it is not quite like anything else I have found there. It threw off a lot of bright white spores, so I’m sure it is Tricholoma. The cap was very viscid and smooth, no scaling going on, so I’m pretty sure it is not something like imbricatum or vaccinum. It is not fracticum, although viscid, and right now I can’t remember if dryophilus is viscid, but it doesn’t quite look like that. So it is a brown to brownish capped Tricholoma, but not one I know… so I am tossing it into the pessundatum gp., like Arora did. When I can get a copy of the Tricholoma section of Agaricales of CA (why are those so pricy?), I’ll see if there is one there that matches this better.

1/29/2007 – ok, I was able to spend some time going over the Agaricales of CA this past weekend, and spent some time in the Tricholoma section. After going back and forth I found T. manzanitae, which pretty much exactly matched this sample. Also, this was found in among live oak, but right where a largish patch of manzanita was starting about 15-20 feet away.

And finally, I’m confused enough, I’m just going to drop these back to ‘sp.’. T. manazitae should be white at first, then salmon-orange in color, and dull brown in age. This does seem to look like the salmon-orange stage. But it should also have radial scaling on the cap, which this doesn’t. So, this one close to T. dryophilum, and T. manzanitae, and I didn’t spend enough time with the thing to figure it out. So, I’m going with ‘sp.’ until I find more, probably next year.
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

description:
These are kinda like the photos I set out to take really, although it hard to see why. But this species in the guides, always is photo’ed with lots of fluffy scales hanging of the cap edges and stipe. But you really never find this one with scales like that, usually you find it looking either like this, or even smoother. So, here is a kinda half-way photo. There are scales, and left over ones on the dried leaves, but mostly the sample is smooth. So, I think these are fairly good, in trying to photo the species as it is.

But on the other hand it was in shadow, and looks too grey. And kinda neat with the layer of ice crystals covering the cap.
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

description:
Ok, I’m going with R. eccentrica on these, and giving up on the R. subnigricans, because of the notes by Thiers in the Agaricales of CA. One thing he seems to be off in the description, that Arora does get, is the disgusting smell when these get old. When young they smell fine, or not much at all. But old they start to develop a vomit odor.

The staining is distinctive on these, because it is sooooo slow. It does almost nothing at first, and takes 10mins to get to a red brown, and then another 20 mins for that to fade, and then ends up a brown-grey.

(I think I said this before, I’m starting to repeat myself…)
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

description:
Hadn’t seen these up there before, and kinda neat. The second photo is from the next morning to try and get as much of the greenish tint of the lamellae, which is kinda a minty hue. But the green, which is slight, didn’t come out very well in the photo.

But these are different than the R. brevipes, esp. in the lamellae. They are kinda soft and thin, almost hygrophorus like, where the R. brevipes lamellae are pretty brittle and thick, and break up into peices when you rub them.

I think there is a better name for this one now, R. chloriodes? To suggest the green is like chlorine I guess. But I can’t remember a ref. to this one, I should google it, or someone could point it out?

description: These are kinda neat. I haven’t seen this species up there before, but I also found one really old one near by, so I am pretty sure about the species of these buttons. But also I had never seen buttons of this species before, and there are some neat features. The “egg” doesn’t seem to have any complete universal veil, that is only seen as the crumblies on the forming caps. The left over “egg” tissue will eventually become scally rings on the mature stipe. In the second photo, the forming partial veil tissue is bright yellow, which also points to the species.

description: Ok, here it is, one more observation over a week later. I found this pine cone with a couple obviously bird nest fungus on it. But the mushrooms were still small orange domes, and I wasn’t sure which ones they were. So, I brought it home with me from Albion, and kept it on the back porch for a week, for the mushrooms to mature. And here they are, the orange caps dried out, and started to flake off. The “eggs” are dark grey, and stuck together with glue. The outsides are whitish and fuzzy, so that points to the species. First time it took me over a week to make an observation…

One more unknown here (although I could add about 6 more unknown Russulas, really need to get better with Russulas (and a few more unknown Ramarias, but I digress…)…). Kinda a purple Cortinarius-y kinda guy. But the interesting thing is the funny smallish cap compared to the stipe. And a close up of the lamellae, shows how they are small, undeveloped and with roughened edges. So, not sure what to make of this one, but kinda neat.

A nice little, really little Lepiota here. Found in a redwood grove. The clean stipe, and scaling of the cap points to L. cristata, but it is too small, and the scaling isn’t a thick as I usually see in cristata. Arora states that there a number of small Lepiotas which are similar to cristata, but microscopically different, and I think this is one of them. I was going to dry it, and pass it on to Else Vellinga here, but it was so small, and very thin and fragile, that it had completely fallen apart to nothing by the time I got it home. So, sorry about that. But a nice little mushroom nonetheless.

These are kinda cute. They are smallish, about 2-3cm in the cap size, ~10cm long in the stipe. The spore color is a nice darker brown/rusty brown, so I am pretty sure these are Cortinarius. They were not visid at all anywhere, the cap are probably hygrophanous, but I didn’t verify that. The contina seems to have complete gone away on the stipe, but there seems to have been a universal veil, there are brown veil remenants on the cap edges, and the bottom of the stipes are wooly white with veil remenants. Kinda neat little guys, found in the duff of a redwood grove. But no idea about the species.

Feb 23, 2007 – I just got “Mushrooms and other fungi of North America” by Roger Phillips, and I look at the cover, and I think, hey that it my little cort. with wooly stipe right there. I look inside, and it take a little looking, but I find that on the cover is C. evernius. Which it turns out is described in Arora also. The description actually matches well, with the veil remnants on the cap edge, and the white wooly veil on the stipe. But I had dismissed it do to the size of the cap, and the stalk description says it is equal or narrowed to the base. This better matches the photos in Phillips. These seem to be too small, and the stalks are wider at the base. But the photos do look similar.

In the comments for C. evernius Arora mention C. lucorum as a common conifer lover which differs with a club shaped stem. These are under D. fir and Redwood, and mostly club shaped, so I will go with that.

Feb. 24, 2007 — after looking over a google search on C. lucorum, these do look very close, but the photos I found have an abrupt bulb at the base, where these are more smoothly club shaped. I guess I should just go for the main species in Arora first, before heading to the notes, if I really just can’t tell the difference here. I’m calling these C. evernius, although they could be C. lucorum, or C. saturinius which is a similar European species that has been seen (maybe) in Oregon.

Found these near some H. crustuliniforme, but these are very small, about 2cm in the cap. The stipes seem to be too long, and the pileus shape not right for H. crust. I have a spore print and is a nice brown color. So, I think these are also Hebeloma, but not sure what species…

Ok, this is the second year I have found these. Cute little buttons here, last year someone found larger more domed ones, with a slightly darked brown cap (kinda a light tan color). I have a spore print, that I will get around to photo’ing here, and it is brown. Not sure if you want to call it light brown, or dark brown, or rusty-brown, I’ll just call it brown.

Something about these looks like Hebeloma, with no veil, but not sure. They are fairly small mushrooms, but just another LBJ type Hebeloma here…

ID’ed from their growth on pine needles, not on rotting logs. In one place where I was, there were many, many 100’s of these covering the pine needles. For some reason this was the first time these were found up there.
These are young buttons, grown in a nice wet climate, so they still have the dark green-grey-brown color. But this species can have many colors in the cap depending on wetness and amount of sunlight.
ID’ed from the slight blueing of the cap context when cut.
This is a weird cluster of these, haven’t seen this type of cluster before… usually these are single, or only 2-3 together.

I think one of the field marks for these is that the lamellae (gills) stick out from the pileus (cap) when fully grown, like you can see from the second photo, where the edges of the gills are wider than the cap face. Also like in the buttons, it has that nice deep wine-red color, like a good Sirah (hmm… that gives me an idea).

First time these were listed for the area, not sure why, I know I’ve found them up there before. Probably just didn’t get around to ID, since usually things like russula, corts and suillus are left to the end. These are genera that are easy to tell the genus, but more difficult to tell the species.

But subnigricans is the older name, and it is listed as such in Arora. Agaricales of CA lists these are R. eccentrica, and states they are a different species from the other R. subnigricans. They can be told from the usually off-center stipe, the bruising colors which goes very slowly (usually takes 30 mins to complete) to red, to red-brown, and then grey-brown (but not black). And in the older ones I can tell the odor, which is disgusting… much like vomit at times.

I created some fresh bruises on the right hand stipe in the photo, and waited 5-10 mins for the red-brown color to deepen for the photo. But then the stipe was in shadow, so it hard to get the color of the bruise from this photo. Oh well.

Ok, going with R. eccentrica on these, changed observation so it can get listed along with other eccentrica.

First time I had seen these. I was told they came from near the airport. Just big clumpy balls, the young smaller ones had pinkish tones, the older ones are darker. The insides are kinda colorless. They are kinda like rubber balls, and can actually bounce. The bit out of the last photo is really a bite, the squirels had been nibbling on the older ones.
Kinda old specimens here…

This one came in and was rather slimy, much more than most Ramaria I’ve seen. When you cut it open the stalks were filled with clear areas, kinda like solid gelatin. This one doesn’t quite fit the description in Arora, but in the notes there is listed a R. gelatinaurantia, which might fit better. With the bright orange, yellow-orange stalks, and a band of just yellow at ground level. But the species list for the area had R. gelatinosa as found before, so I didn’t think this one different enough to merit a new species listing. Although it might be this slightly different similar species.
Pretty much the easiest of the ramarias to id.

First time I had seen this one, and the blueing of the gills was very slight here. There is supposed to be two blue lines in the gills in the second photo. If you look close you can see just a little blue here…

Moving this to P. arenicola from Darvin’s notes.
First time found up there, probably because they are just too small. I knew I would find them up there eventually here. I finally remembered to pay attention this time and found them.

Ok, I know this ia Leucoagaricus, or whatever, but I haven’t gotten around to changing my lists yet, so it is Lepiota for now.
Ok, now Leucoagaricus.

Ok, not really sure about these. The real difference on these was a fairly fuzzy edge to the pileus. But it wasn’t fuzzy enough for a L. torminosus, plus there aren’t any birch or aspen in Mendocino that I know of. Looking at the notes in Arora for L. torminosus, there is a mention of L. subvillosus, so we called these they. But it would be good to compare to more samples in the future.

First time these were found up there, and I found a lot of them, so no idea why they weren’t found before…

They ooze white latex that doesn’t stain, stays bright white, and doesn’t stain the gills. They are fairly hefty for a latarius, much too big to be rubidus, and kinda dark colored, so not sure what they were.

When you taste them, with a little nibble of the edge of the cap, they are burning acrid. But strangely it takes some time for the acrid to kick in, at first nothing, then bitter, then peppery, then 20-30 secs. later very acrid.
You can see the purple staining of the gills from the latex in the second photo.
People have mostly been calling these L. rubidus, instead of L. fragilis var. rubidus. I might change the name later, but it is still in this name in my lists for now.

Ok, this species is confused, some call it I. rimosa, and others call it I. sororia. John Brown, who is doing a study of CA inocybe is calling it : “I. sororia (Stuntz)”, until it can finially get clarified. Somehow it has gotten labelled rimosa in my lists, but Arora has it as sororia, so I should probably change my lists to I. sororia for now.
Changing lists now to sororia.

Found lots of these this year, in lots of different places. It was a really goor year for these. Don’t really know why there are “false chanterelles”, they don’t look anything like them to me. The one chanterelle I found this year was in the middle of a patch of these, and it was clearly different.
These were just barely coming up at this point, just small buttons found this year.

Usually we only find a few of these each year, although we always found some each year. But this year, I was able to find 100’s and 100’s of these, in one redwood grove there were just everywhere, growing in lines among the deep redwood duff.

The second photo shows darker brown patches on one cap, these are not part of the mushroom, but are spore prints from a neighboring mushroom. So, that gives you an idea of the spore color.

I hate gymnopus, someone needs to explain to me, what makes a gymnopus a gymnopus. All the gymnopus I see seem to be completely different looking species. It seems to be the genus of — ok it has white spores, and I don’t know what else it is, so put it in gymnopus for now.

Anyway, I gathered quite a few of these in the field, there were 100’s in this one place. But then I forgot to get around to getting a goof photo when I got back, so this is all I have. I still need a good photo on these…
The bottom two photos here have the Gomphidius growing right up against a S. lakei, and I found these growing close together all day this day.

These were id’ed because of their growth on rotting dead conifer, and lack of Stereum growing on the same logs. This seperates it from Tremella, which in otherwise it looks just the same. Although microscopically they are very different, but we don’t have a scope up there, nor time in one day to use the scope when going through over 100 species of mushrooms.

Ok, I need to go back to this, I think we wanted these listed as vinicolor, but somehow it is coming up in the list as rutilus… Someone wrote it down as this, but we’ve had confusions in Chroogumphus in the past, so I don’t know, I’ll check where this got listed and get back to ya…

Actaully found enough of these this year, that people were able to compare these with B. chrysenteron, and you can tell the difference. Mostly it is in the feel of the pileus, which is thicker and plasticy fealing in the zelleri, and thiner and velvet feeling in the chrysenteron. Also the zelleri is completely red in the stipe, more yellow in the pores, less likely to have cracks in the cap.

Ok, this one. It came in and it was rather large, pileus ~14 cm across, ~5 cm thick. But the feel of the mushroom, was different than anyone we found before. Only the pores stain blue, not the pileus or stipe. And later when I cut in half, the flesh did not stain blue when bruised. Only the flesh near the pores very slowly slightly stained blue. The taste of the flesh was very mild. One interesting feature, there was a layer of brick/vineasous red under the pileapelus (how do I spell that?). You can see a little of this in the photo where there are a few nips out of the edges of the pileus.

The species of B. smithii was roughly placed up at Albion, and I took these home to look at the Boletus of CA. online:

http://mykoweb.com/boletes/index.html

From the field key, B. spadiceus seemed to match these. It does have the red layer in the cap, and the slightly bluing near to the pores only. But these are too large for the description, and the red on the stipe is not mentioned. Also B. fragrans comes close, it better matches size, and has the red on the stipe, but not the red layer in the cap. Also B. fragrans is listed as only a montane species, that has only rearely been found. So, none of these are really satisfactory.

But going back to B. smithii, the description does match these rather well, with the red layer in the cap, and esp. with the rad band at the top of the stipe. But smithii is supposed to blue stain in the flesh, and these didn’t do that much. But I was cutting it up 24 hours later, and in other species the blue staining can go away after getting the sample out of ground, so don’t know. Also I am used to crysenteron, where the amount of bluing in the flesh is quite variable.

The one place the field key went a little wrong with these, was that they are supposed to have a red/pinkish cap. In the comments it does mention that they are usually olive/brown/gray in the cap, but this layer wears off as the species grows and the under red layer starts to show through, giving them a pinkish/red cap look. These are fresh enough to not quite show the red layer in the cap very much.

The description also mentions that these are more common in Oregon and Washington area, but are common enough in the coastal area of CA in Mendocino Co under conifers, but nowhere else in CA. So, in the end, B. smithii sounds good to me.

We were kinda cleaning up at the end of the day, around 11pm, pretty tired of mushrooms and ID at that point, and found another pile of unknowns on a side table that never made it to the main table. In this forgetten pile were these.

They are kinda neat, with the aborted, half formed gills, and the seeping latex when cut are the hall marks of Arcangeliella. Arora has one listed as A. crassa, with a photo there. But the photo doesn’t really match these. In the notes it states that A. crassa really is a montane species, and there is a coastal species, which also has a better formed stipe — A. varigata. So, for now I will claim these are they.

Ok, this happens every year, there is some species which is found in huge numbers, and somehow I just don’t get around to getting a photo. Either I just forget, or I think I have a photo, or something, it just falls through the cracks of trying to get ~400 photos in ~4 hours.

But there were lots of these this year, and good samples. I wanted to get a good photo for comparison to see differences between this and pachycolea. But I guess that will wait until next year…
I think this is a the right species, the one with the white cap, and rooting base…
Once again, calling this one A. lanei until someone can make sense of the species name for these…

This sample was massive, about a foot across. Before people had only found small, 2-3 inch wide samples of this species up there. You can see all the finger pints on the pores, as it was passed around a lot before I was able to get the photo. Also a large piece broke off, oh well, I take what I can get.

It was a very good year for these, lots and lots found. I never find these in the spots I check, and this year I also found lots. Most of them were gathered up that evening and eaten as an appitizer for dinner. Pretty good really.
This was the first time these were found on this foray, well since people have been keeping records of some kind…
Pretty good year for Agaricus, relatively speaking. Found four species this year, more than in the past.
Found a few of these a few weeks ago, but then they seemed to go away. But the rains here this week have brought them back. Patches of 2-6 in little knots are poking up from the ground around here.

Some unknown Nolanea. Not sure what it was when found, kinda Mycena-ish, but the cap was kinda silky radially, and dark. It was Mycena size though, with a 1 cm cap, and ~3 cm long, with very thin 2-3 mm stipe. This gills are mostly free, but hard to tell being so small. The spore print came in very light brown, I guess kinda pinkish.

The radial silky cap, the spore color, the conical cap shape with slight umbo, all point to Nolanea. But I don’t have anything that discribes a Nolenea this small.
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

description: This is kinda a nice grouping showing a few light caps with the darker caps.

description:
This one is the big find of the week. There were a few days of frost, so not much found, most everything all gone this week. But these were kinda hard to see, only one was just poking up from the oak leaf duff, and only part of the cap. When I picked it up, I then noticed the other humps nearby, and there were a couple dozen of these in this one area. They seem to fruit 2-3 inches below ground and push their way up through the dirt and duff.

They are largish size, and at first I thought they were Tricholoma, although I haven’t see some with this universal veil tissue on the cap like this. But then looking at the fiberous caps, and the darker gills of the older ones it came to be later – Inocybe. At home the spore print was brown confirming it.

Looking it up, with the brown caps, and the white veil tissue on the center of the caps got me to the species.

From field notes: 
K. Rogers and I decided to chase after the recently reported Brown Boobies (K. Slauson, R. Hewit). Shortly after arriving at the HSU Marine Lab parking area at 1pm and scoping (Kowa TSN822 20-60x, Leica 20-60x) the near-shore rocks, we both spotted what appeared to be a JUVENILE BROWN BOOBY flying from behind Flat Iron Rock out over the water to the south and then back, disappearing behind the rock. The bird did this about 5 times and then stayed behind the rock. More than likely the bird was looking for a perch and then found one. The bird we saw flying was dark brown above, with a paler brown belly and underwing lining. The bird was long winged with a distinctly pointy head/bill and pointy tail end. We were unable to relocate the bird. (Note: as of 5 Dec this and the following adult bird have been seen simultaneously according to K. Burton & C. Ogan.)

We decided to hike up Trinidad Head to get a better view of the south end of Flat Iron. From a bench area about 100 feet from the pavement end, we scoped the rock and found an ADULT BROWN BOOBY (2:45pm) perched and preening on the south end of the rock. We had excellent views of the bird and observed it for about 15 minutes. Photos are cropped. The adult bird had an obvious white belly with a distinct dark brown chest. The bill was pale yellow. The feet were unseen. The back was uniformly brown. This bird was later sighted by S. Harris, K. Ross, and other Humboldt County birders on 3, 4, & 5 Dec 2006.
A long-staying individual.
